50|$|In the 1970s {{the name}} Damaraland was revived for a <b>bantustan</b> in South West Africa (present-day Namibia), {{intended}} by the apartheid {{government to be}} a self-governing homeland for the Damara people. A centrally administered local government was created in 1980. The <b>bantustan</b> Damaraland was situated on {{the western edge of}} the territory that had been known as Damaraland in the 19th century.|$|E
40|$|ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS: I {{would like}} to thank Professor Bryan Graham for his time and {{valuable}} advice throughout the semester. I {{would also like to thank}} Ashley Langer for all her help with my research, and Professor Roger Craine for his advice and motivation in the initial stages of my workABSTRACT: During the apartheid period, the South African government adopted policies that forced the African population that could not contribute to the economy of „white ‟ South Africa to move to <b>Bantustans</b> or „homelands‟. Moreover, these <b>Bantustans</b> were encouraged to accept „independence ‟ so that the „white ‟ South African government did not have to manage their affairs. These government policies had adverse effects on the lives of the African population. In this paper, I focus on health policies and try to analyze the impact of health inputs on the health of African children, particularly those living in the <b>Bantustans.</b> This paper finds a positive effect of health inputs (provision of a health facility, health expenditure per capita) on the health of the African children, particularly those living in independent <b>Bantustans.</b> ...|$|R
